[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In mathematics and computer science, an **algorithm** (/ˈælɡərɪðəm/ ⓘ) is a finite sequence of mathematically rigorous instructions, typically used to solve a class of specific problems or to perform a computation.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithms are used as specifications for performing calculations and data processing.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] More advanced algorithms can use conditionals to divert the code execution through various routes (referred to as automated decision-making) and deduce valid inferences (referred to as automated reasoning).
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In contrast, a heuristic is an approach to solving problems without well-defined correct or optimal results.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] For example, although social media recommender systems are commonly called "algorithms", they actually rely on heuristics as there is no truly "correct" recommendation.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] As an effective method, an algorithm can be expressed within a finite amount of space and time and in a well-defined formal language for calculating a function.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Starting from an initial state and input, a computation occurs at each step, eventually producing output and terminating.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The transition between states can be non-deterministic; randomized algorithms incorporate random input.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Around 825 AD, Persian scientist and polymath Muḥammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī wrote *kitāb al-ḥisāb al-hindī* ("Book of Indian computation") and *kitab al-jam' wa'l-tafriq al-ḥisāb al-hindī* ("Addition and subtraction in Indian arithmetic").
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In the early 12th century, Latin translations of these texts involving the Hindu–Arabic numeral system and arithmetic appeared, for example *Liber Alghoarismi de practica arismetrice*, attributed to John of Seville, and *Liber Algoritmi de numero Indorum*, attributed to Adelard of Bath.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Here, *alghoarismi* or *algoritmi* is the Latinization of Al-Khwarizmi's name; the text starts with the phrase *Dixit Algoritmi*, or "Thus spoke Al-Khwarizmi".
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The word *algorism* in English came to mean the use of place-value notation in calculations; it occurs in the *Ancrene Wisse* from circa 1225.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] By the time Geoffrey Chaucer wrote *The Canterbury Tales* in the late 14th century, he used a variant of the same word in describing *augrym stones*, stones used for place-value calculation.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In the 15th century, under the influence of the Greek word ἀριθμός (*arithmos*, "number"; *cf.* "arithmetic"), the Latin word was altered to *algorithmus*.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] By 1596, this form of the word was used in English, as *algorithm*, by Thomas Hood.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] One informal definition is "a set of rules that precisely defines a sequence of operations", which would include all computer programs, and any bureaucratic procedure or cook-book recipe.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In general, a program is an algorithm only if it stops eventually.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Step-by-step procedures for solving mathematical problems have been recorded since antiquity.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] This includes in Babylonian mathematics (around 2500 BC), Egyptian mathematics (around 1550 BC), Indian mathematics (around 800 BC and later), the Ifa Oracle (around 500 BC), Greek mathematics (around 240 BC), Chinese mathematics (around 200 BC and later), and Arabic mathematics (around 800 AD).
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The earliest evidence of algorithms is found in ancient Mesopotamian mathematics.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] A Sumerian clay tablet found in Shuruppak near Baghdad and dated to c.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] 2500 BC describes the earliest division algorithm.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] 1600 BC, Babylonian clay tablets described algorithms for computing formulas.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithms were also used in Babylonian astronomy.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Babylonian clay tablets describe and employ algorithmic procedures to compute the time and place of significant astronomical events.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithms for arithmetic are also found in ancient Egyptian mathematics, dating back to the Rhind Mathematical Papyrus c.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithms were later used in ancient Hellenistic mathematics.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Two examples are the Sieve of Eratosthenes, which was described in the *Introduction to Arithmetic* by Nicomachus, and the Euclidean algorithm, which was first described in *Euclid's Elements* (c.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] 300 BC).Examples of ancient Indian mathematics included the Shulba Sutras, the Kerala School, and the Brāhmasphuṭasiddhānta.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In the 9th century, Muḥammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī revolutionized the field by establishing the algorithm as a systematic, finite sequence of logical steps to solve mathematical problems.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In his influential work, The Compendious Book on Calculation by Completion and Balancing, he moved beyond specific numerical solutions to introduce general procedures for algebraic reduction and balancing.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] This transformed mathematics into a 'mechanical' process of well-defined rules—a fundamental shift that laid the groundwork for modern algorithmic theory.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The Latin translation of his arithmetic treatise, titled Algoritmi de numero Indorum, led to the term algorithm being derived from the Latinization of his name, Algoritmi, specifically to describe this new rule-based approach to mathematics.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The first cryptographic algorithm for deciphering encrypted code was developed by Al-Kindi, a 9th-century Arab mathematician, in *A Manuscript On Deciphering Cryptographic Messages*.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] He gave the first description of cryptanalysis by frequency analysis, the earliest codebreaking algorithm.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Weight-driven clocks were a key European invention in Middle Ages, specifically the verge escapement mechanism producing the tick of mechanical clocks.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Accurate automatic machines led to mechanical automata in the 13th century and computational machines—the difference and analytical engines of Charles Babbage and Ada Lovelace in the mid-19th century.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Lovelace designed the first algorithm intended for a computer, Babbage's analytical engine, the first real Turing-complete computer, more than the mechanical calculators of the time.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Although the full implementation of Babbage's second device was only built decades after her lifetime, Lovelace has been called "history's first programmer".
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The Jacquard loom, a precursor to punch cards, and telephone switching machines led to the development of the first computers.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] By the mid-19th century, the telegraph, was in use throughout the world.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] By the late 19th century, ticker tape (c.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] 1910) with its punched-paper use of Baudot code on tape.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Telephone-switching networks of electromechanical relays were invented in 1835.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] These led to the invention of the digital adding device by George Stibitz in 1937.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] While working in Bell Laboratories, he observed the "burdensome" use of mechanical calculators with gears, prompting him to create an experimental digital adder at home.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In 1928, a partial formalization of the modern concept of algorithms began with attempts to solve David Hilbert's *Entscheidungsproblem*(decision problem).
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Later formalizations were framed as attempts to define "effective calculability" or "effective method".
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Those formalizations included the Gödel–Herbrand–Kleene recursive functions of 1930, 1934 and 1935, Alonzo Church's lambda calculus of 1936, Emil Post's Formulation 1 of 1936, and Alan Turing's Turing machines of 1936–37 and 1939.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] For decades, it was assumed that algorithm evolution progresses from heuristics to formal algorithms.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] A Symbolic integration provides a classic illustration.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In 1961, James Slagle’s program SAINT used heuristics to solve 52 of 54 freshman calculus exercises from an MIT textbook (≈96%).
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In 1967, Larry Moses’s SIN refined the heuristics and achieved 100% success, though it remained heuristic.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Finally, in 1969, Robert Risch introduced the Risch Algorithm with formal guarantees.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] This trajectory defined the traditional path: heuristics evolving until a definitive, guaranteed algorithm emerged.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] However, the rise of transformer-based AI has inverted this sequence — classical algorithms are now being displaced by heuristics once again.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithms have evolved and improved in many ways as time goes on.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Common uses of algorithms today include social media apps like Instagram and YouTube.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithms are used as a way to analyze what people like and push more of those things to the people who interact with them.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Quantum computing uses quantum algorithm procedures to solve problems faster.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] More recently, in 2024, NIST updated their post-quantum encryption standards, which includes new encryption algorithms to enhance defenses against attacks using quantum computing.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithms can be expressed in many kinds of notation, including natural languages, pseudocode, flowcharts, drakon-charts, programming languages or control tables.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Natural language expressions of algorithms tend to be verbose and ambiguous and are rarely used for complex or technical algorithms.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Pseudocode, flowcharts, drakon-charts, and control tables are structured expressions of algorithms that avoid common ambiguities of natural language.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Programming languages are primarily for expressing algorithms in a computer-executable form but are also used to define or document algorithms.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithm representations can also be classified into three accepted levels of Turing machine description: high-level description, implementation description, and formal description.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] A high-level description describes the qualities of the algorithm itself, ignoring how it is implemented on the Turing machine.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] An implementation description describes the general manner in which the machine moves its head and stores data to carry out the algorithm, but does not give exact states.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In the most detail, a formal description gives the exact state table and list of transitions of the Turing machine.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] A flowchart is a graphical aid that describes and documents an algorithm.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] It has four primary symbols: arrows showing program flow, rectangles (SEQUENCE, GOTO), diamonds representing decisions, and dots (OR-tie).
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Sub-structures can "nest" in rectangles, but only if a single exit occurs from the superstructure.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] It is often important to know the time, storage, or other cost an algorithm may require.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Methods have been developed to analyse algorithms to estimate these needs.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] For example, an algorithm that adds up the elements of a list of *n* numbers would have a time requirement of ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠, using big O notation.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The algorithm only needs to remember two values: the sum of all the elements so far, and its current position in the input list.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] If the space required to store the input numbers is not counted, it has a space requirement of ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠, otherwise ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ is required.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Different algorithms may complete the same task with a different set of instructions in less or more time, space, or 'effort' than others.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] For example, a binary search algorithm (with cost ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠) outperforms a sequential search (cost ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ ) when used for table lookups on sorted lists.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The analysis, and study of algorithms is a discipline of computer science.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithms are often studied abstractly, without referencing a specific programming language or implementation.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Like other mathematical disciplines, it focuses on the algorithm's properties, not implementation.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Pseudocode is typical for analysis as it is a simple and general representation.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Most algorithms are implemented on particular hardware/software platforms and their algorithmic efficiency is tested using real code.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The efficiency of a particular algorithm may be insignificant for many "one-off" problems but it can be critical for algorithms designed for fast, interactive, commercial, or long-life scientific usage.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Increasing the input size often exposes inefficient algorithms that are otherwise benign.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Empirical testing is useful for uncovering unexpected interactions that affect performance.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Benchmarks may be used to compare before/after potential improvements to an algorithm after program optimization.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Empirical tests cannot fully replace formal analysis, and are difficult to perform fairly.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] To illustrate the potential improvements possible even in well-established algorithms, a recent significant innovation, relating to FFT algorithms used for image processing, can decrease processing time up to 1,000 times for medical imaging.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In general, speed improvements depend on special properties of the problem, which are very common in practical applications.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The best case of an algorithm refers to the scenario or input for which the algorithm or data structure takes the least time and resources to complete its tasks.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The worst case of an algorithm is the case that causes the algorithm or data structure to consume the maximum period of time and computational resources.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithm design may take advantage of many different approaches, such as divide-and-conquer or dynamic programming.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Techniques for designing and implementing algorithms are also called algorithm design patterns.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Examples include the template method pattern and the decorator pattern.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] An important aspect of algorithm design is efficient use of resources such as memory or time; the big O notation is used to describe how resource use changes as the size of inputs increase.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Any algorithm can be computed by any Turing complete model.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Turing completeness only requires four instruction types—conditional GOTO, unconditional GOTO, assignment, HALT.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Tausworthe augments the three Böhm-Jacopini canonical structures: SEQUENCE, IF-THEN-ELSE, and WHILE-DO, with two more: DO-WHILE and CASE.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] An additional benefit of a structured program is that it lends itself to proofs of correctness using mathematical induction.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] By themselves, algorithms are not usually patentable.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In the United States, a claim consisting solely of simple manipulations of abstract concepts, numbers, or signals does not constitute "processes", so algorithms are not patentable (as in *Gottschalk v.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] However, practical applications of algorithms can be patentable.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Diehr*, the application of a simple feedback algorithm to aid in the curing of synthetic rubber was deemed patentable.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The patenting of software is controversial, and there are criticized patents involving algorithms, especially data compression algorithms, such as Unisys's LZW patent.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Additionally, some cryptographic algorithms have export restrictions (see export of cryptography).
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Problems may be suited for one implementation or the other.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] is a puzzle commonly solved using recursive implementation.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Every recursive version has an equivalent (but possibly more or less complex) iterative version, and vice versa.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Algorithms are usually discussed with the assumption that computers execute one instruction of an algorithm at a time on serial computers.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Parallel algorithms take advantage of computer architectures where multiple processors can work on a problem at the same time.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Distributed algorithms use multiple machines connected via a computer network.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Parallel and distributed algorithms divide the problem into sub-problems and collect the results back together.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Resource consumption in these algorithms is not only processor cycles on each processor but also the communication overhead between the processors.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Some sorting algorithms can be parallelized efficiently, but their communication overhead is expensive.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Iterative algorithms are generally parallelizable, but some problems have no parallel algorithms and are called inherently serial problems.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] seek an approximation that is close to the true solution.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Such algorithms have practical value for many hard problems.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] , where there is a set of items, and the goal is to pack the knapsack to get the maximum total value.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Each item has some weight and some value.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The total weight that can be carried is no more than some fixed number X.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] So, the solution must consider the weights of items as well as their value.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Another way of classifying algorithms is by their design methodology or paradigm.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Brute force is a problem-solving method of systematically trying every possible option until the optimal solution is found.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] This approach can be very time-consuming, testing every possible combination of variables.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] It is often used when other methods are unavailable or too complex.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Brute force can solve a variety of problems, including finding the shortest path between two points and cracking passwords.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] ) until the instances are small enough to solve easily.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] is an example of divide and conquer, where an unordered list is repeatedly split into smaller lists, which are sorted in the same way and then merged.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] , which solves one smaller instance of itself, and does not require a merge step.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] specifies rules for moving around a graph and is useful for such problems.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Such algorithms make some choices randomly (or pseudo-randomly).
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] They find approximate solutions when finding exact solutions may be impractical (see heuristic method below).
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms always return the correct answer, but their running time is only probabilistically bound, e.g.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] is not dominated by the resulting reduced algorithms.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] finds the median of an unsorted list by first sorting the list (the expensive portion), and then pulling out the middle element in the sorted list (the cheap portion).
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In this approach, multiple solutions are built incrementally and abandoned when it is determined that they cannot lead to a valid full solution.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] When searching for optimal solutions to a linear function bound by linear equality and inequality constraints, the constraints can be used directly to produce optimal solutions.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] A linear programming algorithm can solve such a problem if it can be proved that all restrictions for integer values are superficial, i.e., the solutions satisfy these restrictions anyway.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In the general case, a specialized algorithm or an algorithm that finds approximate solutions is used, depending on the difficulty of the problem.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] can be found using the shortest path to the goal from all adjacent vertices.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Unlike divide and conquer, dynamic programming subproblems often overlap.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The difference between dynamic programming and simple recursion is the caching or memoization of recursive calls.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] When subproblems are independent and do not repeat, memoization does not help; hence dynamic programming is not applicable to all complex problems.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Using memoization dynamic programming reduces the complexity of many problems from exponential to polynomial.
