[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Such algorithms start with some solution and improve it by making small modifications.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] The most popular use of greedy algorithms is finding minimal spanning trees of graphs without negative cycles.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] are greedy algorithms that can solve this optimization problem.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] find solutions close to the optimal solution when finding the optimal solution is impractical.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] These algorithms get closer and closer to the optimal solution as they progress.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In principle, if run for an infinite amount of time, they will find the optimal solution.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] They can ideally find a solution very close to the optimal solution in a relatively short time.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Some, like simulated annealing, are non-deterministic algorithms while others, like tabu search, are deterministic.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] One of the simplest algorithms finds the largest number in a list of numbers of random order.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Finding the solution requires looking at every number in the list.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Assume the first number in the set is the largest.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] For each remaining number in the set: if this number is greater than the current largest, it becomes the new largest.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] When there are no unchecked numbers left in the set, consider the current largest number to be the largest in the set.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] Artificial intelligence systems have been used to discover and optimize algorithms.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaDev, a reinforcement learning system based on AlphaZero that discovered improved sorting and hashing algorithms.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In a paper published in *Nature*, AlphaDev was reported to have discovered small sorting algorithms that outperformed previously known human benchmarks and were integrated into the LLVM standard C++ sorting library.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] In 2025, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaEvolve, an evolutionary coding agent powered by large language models for general-purpose algorithm discovery and optimization.
[src:css-layout-api/algorithm] AlphaEvolve uses language models to propose code changes, automated evaluators to test candidate solutions, and an evolutionary process to improve promising algorithms over multiple iterations.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] It’s been available across browsers since April 2021.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] The **`Worklet`** interface is a lightweight version of Web Workers and gives developers access to low-level parts of the rendering pipeline.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] With Worklets, you can run JavaScript and WebAssembly code to do graphics rendering or audio processing where high performance is required.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] Worklets allow static import of ECMAScript modules, if supported, using `import`.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] Dynamic import is disallowed by the specification — calling `import()` will throw.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] Worklets are restricted to specific use cases; they cannot be used for arbitrary computations like Web Workers.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] The `Worklet` interface abstracts properties and methods common to all kind of worklets, and cannot be created directly.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] For 3D rendering with WebGL, you don't use worklets.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] Instead, you write vertex shaders and fragment shaders using GLSL code, and those shaders will then run on the graphics card.
[src:css-layout-api/api-worklet] Adds the script module at the given URL to the current worklet.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] The **CSS containment** module defines containment and container queries.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] Containment enables the isolation of page subtrees from the rest of the DOM.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] The browser can then improve performance by optimizing the rendering of these independent parts.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] Container queries are similar to dimension media queries, except that the queries are based on the dimensions of a specific container element defined as a containment context, rather than on the dimensions of the viewport.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] Container queries enable querying a container's size, properties, property values, or even just its assigned `container-name` to conditionally apply CSS styles.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] When applying these conditional styles, you can use container query length units, which specify lengths relative to the dimensions of the query container.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] Additional properties are defined to enable establishing a specific element as a query container and giving it a specific name.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] A guide to using container queries with `@container`, including naming containment contexts.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] Describes the basic aims of CSS containment and how to leverage `contain` and `content-visibility` for a better user experience.
[src:css-layout-api/css-containment] A guide to writing container size and style queries with `@container`, including style queries for custom properties, query syntax and names, and nesting container queries.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Houdini is a set of low-level APIs that exposes parts of the CSS engine, giving developers the power to extend CSS by hooking into the styling and layout process of a browser's rendering engine.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Houdini is a group of APIs that give developers direct access to the CSS Object Model (CSSOM), enabling developers to write code the browser can parse as CSS, thereby creating new CSS features without waiting for them to be implemented natively in browsers.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Houdini enables faster parse times than using JavaScript `HTMLElement.style` for style changes.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Browsers parse the CSSOM — including layout, paint, and composite processes — before applying any style updates found in scripts.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] In addition, layout, paint, and composite processes are repeated for JavaScript style updates.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Houdini code doesn't wait for that first rendering cycle to be complete.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Rather, it is included in that first cycle — creating renderable, understandable styles.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Houdini provides an object-based API for working with CSS values in JavaScript.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Houdini's CSS Typed Object Model API is a CSS Object Model with types and methods, exposing values as JavaScript objects making for more intuitive CSS manipulation than previous string based `HTMLElement.style` manipulations.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Every element and style sheet rule has a style map which is accessible via its `StylePropertyMap`.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] A feature of CSS Houdini is the `Worklet`.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] With worklets, you can create modular CSS, requiring a single line of JavaScript to import configurable components: no pre-processors, post-processors or JavaScript frameworks needed.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] This added module contains `PaintWorkletGlobalScope.registerPaint` functions, which register completely configurable worklets.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] The CSS `paint()` function is an additional function supported by the `<image>` type.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] It takes parameters that include the name of the worklet, plus additional parameters needed by the worklet.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] The worklet also has access to the element's custom properties: they don't need to be passed as function arguments.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] In the following example the `paint()` function is passed a worklet called `my-component`.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Below you can find links to the main reference pages covering the APIs that fall under the Houdini umbrella, along with links to guides to help you if you need guidance in learning how to use them.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Defines an API for registering new CSS properties.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Properties registered using this API are provided with a parse syntax that defines a type, inheritance behavior, and an initial value.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Converting CSSOM value strings into meaningfully typed JavaScript representations and back can incur a significant performance overhead.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] The CSS Typed OM exposes CSS values as typed JavaScript objects to allow their performant manipulation.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Developed to improve the extensibility of CSS, the Painting API allows developers to write JavaScript functions that can draw directly into an element's background, border, or content via the `paint()` CSS function.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] An API for running scripts in various stages of the rendering pipeline independent of the main JavaScript execution environment.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Worklets are conceptually similar to Web Workers, and are called by and extend the rendering engine.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] Designed to improve the extensibility of CSS, this API enables developers to write their own layout algorithms, like masonry or line snapping.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] An API exposing the CSS parser more directly, for parsing arbitrary CSS-like languages into a mildly typed representation.
[src:css-layout-api/guide-houdini] An API exposing font metrics, giving access to typographic layout results.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] In graphic design, **page layout** is the arrangement of visual elements on a page.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] It generally involves organizational principles of composition to achieve specific communication objectives.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The high-level page layout involves deciding on the overall arrangement of text and images, and possibly on the size or shape of the medium.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] These decisions require intelligence, sentience, and creativity on the part of the designer, and they are informed by culture, psychology, and what the document authors and editors wish to communicate and emphasize.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Low-level pagination and typesetting are more mechanical processes.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Given certain parameters such as boundaries of text areas, the typeface, and font size, text justification can be performed in a straightforward way.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Until desktop publishing became dominant, these processes were still done by people, but in modern publishing, they are almost always automated.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The result might be published as-is (for example, a residential phone book interior) or it might be adjusted by a graphic designer (as for a highly polished, expensive publication).
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Beginning from early illuminated pages in hand-copied books of the Middle Ages and proceeding down to intricate modern magazine and catalog layouts, proper page design has long been a consideration in printed material.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] With print media, elements usually consist of type (text), images (pictures), and occasionally place-holder graphics for elements that are not printed with ink such as die/laser cutting, foil stamping or blind embossing.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The term ***page furniture*** may be used for items on a page other than the main text and images, such as headlines, bylines or image captions.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] With manuscripts, all of the elements are added by hand, so the creator can determine the layout directly as they create the work, perhaps with an advanced sketch as a guide.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] With ancient woodblock printing, all elements of the page were carved directly into the wood, though later layout decisions might need to be made if the printing was transferred onto a larger work, such as a large piece of fabric, potentially with multiple block impressions.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] With the Renaissance invention of letterpress printing and cold-metal moveable type, typesetting was accomplished by physically assembling characters using a composing stick into a galley—a long tray.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Any images would be created by engraving.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The original document would be a hand-written manuscript; if the typesetting was performed by someone other than the layout artist, markup would be added to the manuscript with instructions as to typeface, font size, and so on.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] After the first round of typesetting, a galley proof might be printed in order for proofreading to be performed, either to correct errors in the original, or to make sure that the typesetter had copied the manuscript properly, and correctly interpreted the markup.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The final layout would be constructed in a "form" or "forme" using pieces of wood or metal ("furniture") to space out the text and images as desired, a frame known as a chase, and objects which lock down the frame known as quoins.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] This process is called imposition, and potentially includes arranging multiple pages to be printed on the same sheet of paper which will later be folded and possibly trimmed.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] An "imposition proof" (essentially a short run of the press) might be created to check the final placement.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The invention of hot metal typesetting in 1884 sped up the typesetting process by allowing workers to produce slugs—entire lines of text—using a keyboard.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The slugs were the result of molten metal being poured into molds temporarily assembled by the typesetting machine.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The layout process remained the same as with cold metal type, however: assembly into physical galleys.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Offset lithography allows the bright and dark areas of an image (at first captured on film) to control ink placement on the printing press.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] This means that if a single copy of the page can be created on paper and photographed, then any number of copies could be printed.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The type could be set with a typewriter, or to achieve professional results comparable to letterpress, a specialized typesetting machine.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The IBM Selectric Composer, for example, could produce type of different size, different fonts (including proportional fonts), and with text justification.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] With photoengraving and halftone, physical photographs could be transferred into print directly, rather than relying on hand-made engravings.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The layout process then became the task of creating the paste up, so named because rubber cement or another adhesive would be used to physically paste images and columns of text onto a rigid sheet of paper.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Completed pages become known as camera-ready, "mechanical" or "mechanical art".
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Phototypesetting was invented in 1945; after keyboard input, characters were shot one-by-one onto a photographic negative, which could then be sent to the print shop directly, or shot onto photographic paper for paste-up.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] These machines became increasingly sophisticated, with computer-driven models able to store text on magnetic tape.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] As the graphical capabilities of computers matured, they began to be used to render characters, columns, pages, and even multi-page signatures directly, rather than simply summoning a photographic template from a pre-supplied set.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] In addition to being used as display devices for computer operators, cathode-ray tubes were used to render text for phototypesetting.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The curved nature of the CRT display, however, led to distortions of text and art on the screen towards the outer edges of the screens.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The advent of "flat screen" monitors (LCD, LED, and more recently OLED) in 1997 eliminated the distortion problems caused by older CRT displays.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] As of 2016, flat-panel displays have almost completely replaced CRT displays.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Printers attached directly to computers allowed them to print documents directly, in multiple copies, or as an original which could be copied on a ditto machine or photocopier.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] WYSIWYG word processors made it possible for general office users and consumers to make more sophisticated page layouts, use text justification, and use more fonts than were possible with typewriters.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Early dot matrix printing was sufficient for office documents but was of too low a quality for professional typesetting.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Inkjet printing and laser printing did produce sufficient quality type, and so computers with these types of printers quickly replaced phototypesetting machines.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] With modern desktop publishing software such as flagship software Adobe InDesign and cloud-based Marq, the layout process can occur entirely on-screen.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Greyscale images must be either half-toned digitally if being sent to an offset press or sent separately for the print shop to insert into marked areas.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Completed works can also be transmitted digitally to the print shop, who may print it themselves, shoot it directly to film, or use computer to plate technology to skip the physical original entirely.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] PostScript and Portable Document Format (PDF) have become standard file formats for digital transmission.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Since the advent of personal computing, page layout skills have expanded to electronic media as well as print media.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] E-books, PDF documents, and static web pages mirror paper documents relatively closely, but computers can also add multimedia animation, and interactivity.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Page layout for interactive media overlaps with interface design and user experience design; an interactive "page" is better known as a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Modern web pages are typically produced using HTML for content and general structure, cascading style sheets to control presentation details such as typography and spacing, and JavaScript for interactivity.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Since these languages are all text-based, this work can be done in a text editor, or a special HTML editor which may have WYSIWYG features or other aids.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Additional technologies such as Macromedia Flash may be used for multimedia content.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Web developers are responsible for actually creating a finished document using these technologies, but a separate web designer may be responsible for establishing the layout.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A given web designer might be a fluent web developer as well, or may merely be familiar with the general capabilities of the technologies and merely visualize the desired result for the development team.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] While page layout has traditionally referred to print media such as books and magazines, the concept also applies to digital environments.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Early web pages often used table-based layouts to position text and images, but this approach created accessibility and maintenance issues and has since been replaced by CSS-based layouts.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Modern web page layout relies on technologies such as CSS Flexbox and CSS Grid, which provide greater flexibility and semantic structure.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] These techniques support responsive web design, allowing layouts to adapt across devices and screen sizes.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Design guidelines for digital layouts often emphasize usability and accessibility.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] For example, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommends maintaining clear navigation and visual hierarchy to support readability and accessibility.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Common frameworks such as Bootstrap apply these principles in practice across a wide range of websites.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Projected slides used in presentations or entertainment often have similar layout considerations to printed pages.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The magic lantern and opaque projector were used during lectures in the 1800s, using printed, typed, photographed, or hand-drawn originals.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Two sets of photographic film (one negative and one positive) or one reversal film can be used to create positive images that can be projected with light passing through.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Intertitles were used extensively in the earliest motion pictures when sound was not available; they are still used occasionally in addition to the ubiquitous vanity cards and credits.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] It became popular to use transparent film for presentations (with opaque text and images) using overhead projectors in the 1940s, and slide projectors in the 1950s.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Transparencies for overhead projectors could be printed by some photocopiers.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Computer presentation programs became available in the 1980s, making it possible to layout a presentation digitally.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Computer-developed presentations could be printed to a transparency with some laser printers, transferred to slides, or projected directly using LCD overhead projectors.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Modern presentations are often displayed digitally using a video projector, computer monitor, or large-screen television.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Laying out a presentation presents slightly different challenges than a print document, especially because a person will typically be speaking and referring to the projected pages.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Grids and templates are page layout design patterns used in advertising campaigns and multiple-page publications, including websites.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A **grid** is a set of guidelines, able to be seen in the design process and invisible to the end-user/audience, for aligning and repeating elements on a page.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A page layout may or may not stay within those guidelines, depending on how much repetition or variety the design style in the series calls for.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Using a grid to layout elements on the page may require just as much or more graphic design skill than that which was required to design the grid.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] In contrast, a **template** is more rigid.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A template involves repeated elements mostly visible to the end-user/audience.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Using a template to layout elements usually involves less graphic design skill than that which was required to design the template.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Templates are used for minimal modification of background elements and frequent modification (or swapping) of foreground content.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Most desktop publishing software allows for grids in the form of a page filled with coloured lines or dots placed at a specified equal horizontal and vertical distance apart.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Automatic margins and booklet spine (gutter) lines may be specified for global use throughout the document.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Multiple additional horizontal and vertical lines may be placed at any point on the page.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Invisible to the end-user/audience shapes may be placed on the page as guidelines for page layout and print processing as well.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Software templates are achieved by duplicating a template data file, or with master page features in a multiple-page document.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Master pages may include both grid elements and template elements such as header and footer elements, automatic page numbering, and automatic table of contents features.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Static layouts allow for more control over the aesthetics, and thorough optimization of space around and overlapping irregular-shaped content than dynamic layouts.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] In web design, this is sometimes referred to as a fixed width layout; but the entire layout may be scalable in size while still maintaining the original proportions, static placement, and style of the content.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] All raster image formats are static layouts in effect, but a static layout may include searchable text by separating the text from the graphics.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] In contrast, electronic pages allow for dynamic layouts with swapping content, personalization of styles, text scaling, image scaling, or reflowable content with variable page sizes often referred to as fluid or liquid layout.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Dynamic layouts are more likely to separate presentation from content, which comes with its own advantages.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A dynamic layout lays out all text and images into rectangular areas of rows and columns.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] As these areas' widths and heights are defined to be percentages of the available screen, they are responsive to varying screen dimensions.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] They will automatically ensure maximized use of available space while always staying adapted optimally both on-screen resizes and hardware-given restrictions.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Text may freely be resized to provide users' individual needs on legibility while never disturbing a given layout's proportions.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The content's overall arrangement on screen this way may always remain as it was originally designed.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Static layout design may involve more graphic design and visual art skills, whereas dynamic layout design may involve more interactive design and content management skills to thoroughly anticipate content variation.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Motion graphics do not fit neatly into either category, but may involve layout skills or careful consideration of how the motion may affect the layout.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] In either case, the element of motion makes it a dynamic layout, but one that warrants motion graphic design more than static graphic design or interactive design.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Electronic pages may utilize both static and dynamic layout features by dividing the pages or by combining the effects.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] For example, a section of the page such as a web banner may contain static or motion graphics contained within a swapping content area.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Dynamic or live text may be wrapped around irregularly shaped images by using invisible spacers to push the text away from the edges.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Some computer algorithms can detect the edges of an object that contain transparency and flow content around contours.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] With modern media content retrieval and output technology, there is much overlap between visual communications (**front-end**) and information technology (**back-end**).
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Large print publications (thick books, especially instructional in nature) and electronic pages (web pages) require meta data for automatic indexing, automatic reformatting, database publishing, dynamic page display, and end-user interactivity.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Much of the metadata (meta tags) must be hand-coded or specified during the page layout process.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] This divides the task of page layout between artists and engineers, or tasks the artist/engineer to do both.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] More complex projects may require two separate designs: page layout design as the front-end, and function coding as the back-end.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] In this case, the front-end may be designed using an alternative page layout technology such as image editing software or on paper with hand rendering methods.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Most image editing software includes features for converting a page layout for use in a "What You See Is What You Get" (WYSIWYG) editor or features to export graphics for desktop publishing software.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] WYSIWYG editors and desktop publishing software allow front-end design prior to back-end coding in most cases.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Interface design and database publishing may involve more technical knowledge or collaboration with information technology engineering in the front-end.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Sometimes, a function on the back-end is to automate the retrieval and arrangement of content on the front end.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Page layout might be prescribed to a greater or lesser degree by a house style which might be implemented in a specific desktop publishing template.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] There might also be relatively little layout to do in comparison to the amount of pagination (as in novels and other books with no figures).
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] In newspaper production, final selection and cropping of photographs accompanying stories might be left to the layout editor (since the choice of photo could affect the shape of the area needed, and thus the rest of the layout), or there might be a separate photo editor.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Likewise, headlines might be written by the layout editor, a copy editor, or the original author.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] To make stories fit the final layout, relatively inconsequential copy tweaks might be made (for example, rephrasing for brevity), or the layout editor might make slight adjustments to typography elements like font size or leading.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A floating block in writing and publishing is any graphic, text, table, or other representation that is unaligned from the main flow of text.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] The use of floating blocks to present pictures and tables is a typical feature of academic writing and technical writing, including scientific articles and books.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Floating blocks are normally labeled with a caption or title that describes its contents and a number that is used to refer to the figure from the main text.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A common system divides floating block into two separately numbered series, labeled *figure* (for pictures, diagrams, plots, etc.) and *table*.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] An alternative name for figure is **image** or **graphic**.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Floating blocks are said to be *floating* because they are not fixed in position on the page at the place, but rather drift to the side of the page.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] By placing pictures or other large items on the sides of pages rather than embedding them in the middle of the main flow of text, typesetting is more flexible and interruption to the flow of the narrative is avoided.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] For example, an article on geography might have "Figure 1: Map of the world", "Figure 2: Map of Europe", "Table 1: Population of continents", "Table 2: Population of European countries", and so on.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Some books will have a table of figures—in addition to the table of contents—that lists centrally all the figures appearing in the work.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] For digressions from the main narrative.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] For example, a technical manual on the usage of a product might include examples of how various people have employed the product in their work in sidebars.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Equation: Writing on mathematics may place large blocks of mathematical notation in numbered blocks set apart from the main text.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A mockup of a layout might be created to get early feedback, usually before all the content is actually ready.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Whether for paper or electronic media, the first draft of a layout might be simply a rough paper and pencil sketch.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A comprehensive layout for a new magazine might show placeholders for text and images, but demonstrate placement, typographic style, and other idioms intended to set the pattern for actual issues or a particular unfinished issue.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] A website wireframe is a low-cost way to show layout without doing all the work of creating the final HTML and CSS, and without writing the copy or creating any images.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Lorem ipsum text is often used to avoid the embarrassment any improvised sample copy might cause if accidentally published.
[src:css-layout-api/page-layout] Likewise, placeholder images are often labeled "for position only".
